 Topics Learned – Pre Security 
Certificate link: https://tryhackme.com/certificate/THM-TZQCAEWPMM

Tools & Technologies

- Linux Terminal (Bash) — used throughout to navigate file systems, run commands, and interact with services
- TryHackMe AttackBox — browser-based virtual machine for hands-on labs with no local setup required
- Wireshark (intro) — basic exposure to packet capture and network traffic analysis
- nslookup / dig — DNS query tools to understand how domain resolution works
- curl / wget — command-line tools for making HTTP requests and downloading resources
- Windows Command Prompt & PowerShell (intro) — basic Windows CLI navigation

 Key Concepts & Skills Developed

- Understanding the OSI model (7 layers) and how data moves across a network — not just memorizing the layers, but knowing *why* they exist
- How TCP/IP establishes connections, including the three-way handshake (SYN → SYN-ACK → ACK)
- What IP addresses, subnets, and CIDR notation mean and how devices get assigned addresses via DHCP
- How DNS works — from typing a domain name to getting an IP back, including recursive resolvers and TTL
- The HTTP/HTTPS request lifecycle — methods (GET, POST), status codes, headers, and what makes HTTPS different from HTTP
- Linux file system navigation — understanding `/etc`, `/var`, `/home`, permissions (rwx), and why `sudo` matters
- Windows OS fundamentals — NTFS permissions, the registry, Task Manager, and how Windows handles user accounts
- The difference between encryption, encoding, and hashing — and why confusing them is a security mistake
- Basic understanding of Active Directory and why it's the backbone of most corporate networks
- The mindset shift of thinking like an attacker — understanding that vulnerabilities come from misconfigurations and misunderstandings, not just buggy code

